## Polling vs Webhooks

### Current: File-Based Polling (Simple, Works)

```python
# trading/scripts/risk_monitor.py (always-on process)

# Every 30 seconds, check for kill switch
kill_switch = json.load(open('logs/kill_switch.json'))
if kill_switch['enabled']:
    halt_all_trading()
```

```typescript
// Dashboard writes kill switch state to file
await fs.writeFile('logs/kill_switch.json', JSON.stringify({ enabled: true }));
```

**Pros:**
- Simple (no webhooks, no queues)
- Works across filesystem boundaries (Google Drive sync in your case)
- Debugging is trivial (just read the JSON file)

**Cons:**
- Not real-time (30-second polling delay)
- Doesn't scale to 1000s of users (file I/O bottleneck)

### Future: Webhooks or Message Queue

When you have multiple users (>50), switch to:

```typescript
// Dashboard publishes event
await fetch(process.env.TRADING_SYSTEM_WEBHOOK_URL, {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ event: 'kill_switch_enabled', userId: 'abc123' }),
});
```

```python
# trading/scripts/webhook_listener.py (FastAPI)
@app.post("/events")
async def handle_dashboard_event(event: Event):
    if event.type == 'kill_switch_enabled':
        await halt_trading_for_user(event.userId)
```

**When to switch:** File polling breaks at ~50-100 users (too many files to poll).

